1
00:00:04,127 --> 00:00:06,682
I've made this point, 
when I would travel around Russia

2
00:00:07,036 --> 00:00:11,322
that like in Tomsk there is 
a cultural centre,

3
00:00:11,982 --> 00:00:14,913
actually in every Russian town or city

4
00:00:15,091 --> 00:00:16,881
and in other places in the world,

5
00:00:16,920 --> 00:00:23,030
what's in the heart—usually in the
primo location of every city

6
00:00:23,440 --> 00:00:25,938
is a “cultural centre”.

7
00:00:26,388 --> 00:00:29,371
[Boob Culture]

8
00:00:29,888 --> 00:00:33,308
Because people understand, 
this is the...

9
00:00:34,038 --> 00:00:36,432
here are supposed to be on display

10
00:00:36,432 --> 00:00:43,689
the greatest achievements of human
civilization, of human thought.

11
00:00:44,298 --> 00:00:52,498
As the Victorians or Romantics, 
they expressed,

12
00:00:52,721 --> 00:00:54,741
they said, “What is poetry?”

13
00:00:55,550 --> 00:00:58,320
And by extension that means

14
00:01:00,344 --> 00:01:01,593
deep thought.

15
00:01:01,593 --> 00:01:05,928
They said, “The best of what has been 
thought and expressed.”

16
00:01:05,954 --> 00:01:09,222
That's what literature should be, 
and that's what culture should be about—

17
00:01:09,333 --> 00:01:12,543
the best of what has been 
thought and expressed.

18
00:01:13,376 --> 00:01:16,866
So they understand that 
you go to the cultural centre,

19
00:01:17,084 --> 00:01:21,964
and you see the play, 
the ballet, hear the orchestra.

20
00:01:22,754 --> 00:01:23,939
Why?

21
00:01:24,359 --> 00:01:27,683
Because there is an intuitive 
understanding—

22
00:01:27,683 --> 00:01:33,803
this is the zenith point 
of human civilization.

23
00:01:34,273 --> 00:01:35,713
That's the way it was.

24
00:01:35,974 --> 00:01:37,894
Now we have the Internet.

25
00:01:39,650 --> 00:01:43,547
And again, maybe Thoreau, 
another American transcendentalist,
when they told him,

26
00:01:43,682 --> 00:01:46,222
“What do you think 
about the Transatlantic cable?”

27
00:01:47,316 --> 00:01:51,917
That was a cable that went from New York
under the ocean to London.

28
00:01:52,462 --> 00:01:55,281
So they could send messages instantly.

29
00:01:55,424 --> 00:01:56,931
It was like before the Internet.

30
00:01:57,298 --> 00:02:02,470
That was the 19th century 
conception of “wired”.

31
00:02:03,873 --> 00:02:06,402
And when asked what 
he thought about it,

32
00:02:06,402 --> 00:02:08,314
everyone was so excited,

33
00:02:08,314 --> 00:02:12,157
he said, “What if the news is
that the Princess has a cold?”

34
00:02:15,292 --> 00:02:17,806
And that's what the news has become.

35
00:02:18,651 --> 00:02:21,799
This movie started this, 
this person did that...

36
00:02:22,884 --> 00:02:26,138
In the golden age of television

37
00:02:26,517 --> 00:02:30,783
they said that television 
would eradicate ignorance.

38
00:02:31,106 --> 00:02:34,762
After TV there would no longer be
illiterate people.

39
00:02:35,095 --> 00:02:38,026
Everybody through 
the medium of television

40
00:02:38,126 --> 00:02:40,520
would become enlightened.

41
00:02:40,779 --> 00:02:44,152
All knowledge would be available
to them through TV.

42
00:02:44,933 --> 00:02:51,366
In the end, not even, you know, midway...
I was the first television generation.

43
00:02:51,366 --> 00:02:55,101
As now there is Internet generation,
I was in the first television generation.

44
00:02:55,215 --> 00:02:56,725
By the mid-sixties

45
00:02:56,916 --> 00:03:01,520
one of the slang names for TV
was “boob tube”.

46
00:03:01,959 --> 00:03:04,546
“Boob” has different meanings, 
we know.

47
00:03:05,679 --> 00:03:08,369
So it became “boob tube” 
in other ways in time too,

48
00:03:08,724 --> 00:03:13,271
but what they meant at the time by calling 
it “boob tube”—“boob” also means “idiot”.

49
00:03:14,354 --> 00:03:16,413
So it was told, you sit in front of this,

50
00:03:16,831 --> 00:03:19,768
you don't become 
an enlightened thinker,

51
00:03:19,962 --> 00:03:21,605
you become a moron.

52
00:03:22,619 --> 00:03:27,598
A passive, overweight moron.

53
00:03:28,898 --> 00:03:36,726
That was the end result of this
“enlightenment device” called television.

54
00:03:37,182 --> 00:03:40,297
So there's always one or another...

55
00:03:40,644 --> 00:03:44,277
“Plus ça change, 
plus c'est la même chose”—

56
00:03:44,362 --> 00:03:47,926
the French say, “The more things change,
the more they remain the same.”

57
00:03:48,678 --> 00:03:53,626
So, the other day someone showed
a bunch of quotes about...

58
00:03:54,046 --> 00:03:56,880
It appeared to be anti-Internet,

59
00:03:56,880 --> 00:04:02,245
like anti-Twitter, Facebook, on every quote... 
You thought, “Oh, that's what they 
are talking about.”

60
00:04:02,245 --> 00:04:07,917
And actually it was saying like, “Now 
people will stop communicating personally
with one another.”

61
00:04:08,147 --> 00:04:10,730
And there is the whole list 
of quotes like that,

62
00:04:10,730 --> 00:04:14,310
but then at the end it says, 
“These were comments people made

63
00:04:14,440 --> 00:04:17,976
in the 19th century about magazines.”

64
00:04:18,646 --> 00:04:22,690
They were saying: “Now that there are 
magazines... That was going to ruin

65
00:04:23,230 --> 00:04:25,850
human interpersonal relationships.”

66
00:04:26,610 --> 00:04:30,265
So here we are,

67
00:04:32,045 --> 00:04:34,832
13 years into the 21th century:

68
00:04:36,562 --> 00:04:42,642
social networking, Twitter, Instagram...
In the future people will go, “What's was that?”

69
00:04:42,752 --> 00:04:43,993
And someone will go,

70
00:04:44,103 --> 00:04:46,263
— Look it up on Wikipedia.
— What's that?

71
00:04:48,253 --> 00:04:52,373
It will all change—
“Plus ça change, plus c'est la même chose”—

72
00:04:52,373 --> 00:04:54,464
and become more of the same.

73
00:04:58,115 --> 00:05:01,205
“Tell me if there are still
janma, mrityu, jara, vyadhi—

74
00:05:01,239 --> 00:05:07,746
birth, death, old age and disease.
Do a little check-list on that one for me.

75
00:05:07,806 --> 00:05:13,276
I'm willing to bet that 
they are still there.”

76
00:05:14,276 --> 00:05:16,377
They are inescapable.

77
00:05:17,067 --> 00:05:19,489
Mortality is inescapable.

78
00:05:20,007 --> 00:05:23,179
Science hasn't made 
people immortal.

79
00:05:24,177 --> 00:05:27,869
We are searching after amrita, 
which means “nectar”,

80
00:05:27,918 --> 00:05:29,979
and by extension—“immortality”.

81
00:05:30,099 --> 00:05:32,599
It is the search of devas and the asuras,

82
00:05:32,689 --> 00:05:36,620
as we are told,
in the “churning of the ksir ocean”.

83
00:05:36,840 --> 00:05:39,778
And I like to frame this 
in modern sense

84
00:05:39,940 --> 00:05:45,571
that, in one sense, the ultimate pursuit
of theist and atheist

85
00:05:45,871 --> 00:05:47,001
is similar—

86
00:05:47,391 --> 00:05:49,362
everybody wants happiness.

87
00:05:49,362 --> 00:05:50,922
No one can deny

88
00:05:51,302 --> 00:05:53,173
that they want to be happy.

89
00:05:53,373 --> 00:05:59,546
They want love, affection,
a loving affection and happy relationship.

90
00:06:00,066 --> 00:06:04,909
Atheist, theist, agnostic alike.

